            <p> +<lb/> Εἶς θεός, ὁ πάν<lb/>των <choice>
                  <sic>Δεσπότες</sic>
                  <corr>Δεσπότης</corr>
               </choice>.<lb/>
               <choice>
                  <sic>Μνημῖον</sic>
                  <corr>Μνημεῖον</corr>
               </choice> Οὐαλε<lb/>ντίνου Αἰανοῦ, <choice>
                  <abbr>ὑ<lb/>ποδιακ</abbr>
                  <expan>ὑποδιακόνου</expan>
               </choice> ἀποθαν<lb/>όντος μετὰ καλοῦ<lb/>
               <choice>
                  <sic>ὀνόμοτος</sic>
                  <corr>ὀνόματος</corr>
               </choice> καὶ κα<lb/>λῆς πίστεως ἐτῶ<lb/>ν ξʹ, έν <choice>
                  <sic>ἔτι</sic>
                  <corr>ἔτει</corr>
               </choice> τοθʹ ἐν <choice>
                  <sic>μ<lb/>ενὶ</sic>
                  <corr>μηνὶ</corr>
               </choice>
               <choice>
                  <sic> Ἀπελλέου</sic>
                  <corr>Ἀπελλαίου</corr>
               </choice> ιζʹ,<lb/> ἐν ἡμέρᾳ Κυρίου<lb/> δευτέρα.
                        <choice>
                  <sic>Θάρσι</sic>
                  <corr>Θάρσει</corr>
               </choice>, <choice>
                  <sic>ο<lb/>ὐδὶς</sic>
                  <corr>οὐδείς</corr>
               </choice>
                    ἀθάνατος</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:id="zoor0240.translation"
              corresp="#zoor0240.transcription">
            <p> One (is) the God, the Lord of all. Monument of Oualentinos (Valetninus), (son)
                    of Aianus, (the) subdeacon, who died having a good name and good faith (at the
                    age) of 60 years, in the year 379, on (the) 17th (day) of (the) month Apellaios,
                    on the second day of (the) Lord (Monday). Be of good cheer, no one (is)
                    immortal.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The inscription provides the date as the second day of the Lord (Monday), the 17th day of of the month Apellaios, in the year 379 according to the Era of the Province of Arabia, that is December 3, 484 CE. The tombstone is one of about 700 discovered in Byzantine Zoora. The majority of the Greek tombstones from this location have been identified as Christian. The tombstone is rectangular in shape, and curved all around., with chipping on its smoothed, inscribed surface. A rectangular frame surrounds the text. Both are engraved and unpainted. A linear cross with triangular serifs is centered above the frame and deeply engraved. Another cross, this one formed out of four triangles and a central lozenge, is inscribed below the bottom portion of the frame. The script is square, the letters well-cut and aligned. The names Οὐαλεντίνος and Αἰανός are Roman names. The office of subdeacon is mentioned several times at Ghor es-Safi. The inscription includes spelling and grammatical errors.</p>
         </div>
